ASPIKA welcomes Kirsty Heap Friday, April 28th Register at Aspika.com Talks  I was seven years old when I was diagnosed with #Dyslexia, and it impacted my life in different ways both positive and negative.¬†I found school very frustrating and had to spend a lot of extra time doing homework to make sure I achieved the grades I wanted. However, I did learn that my determination and resilience levels are high and that I don‚Äôt like being told that I can‚Äôt or won‚Äôt achieve something!  Looking back now I can see that I hid behind my dyslexia and I let my dyslexia define me in some ways. For example, I didn‚Äôt apply for certain jobs or didn‚Äôt think I‚Äôd be capable of undertaking certain roles because of it. I didn‚Äôt understand my dyslexia, I didn‚Äôt see its benefits until I was in my 30‚Äôs.  I did my master‚Äôs degree in Management with Human Resources in my early 30s whilst working and bringing up my children. This was a three-year process, which was not only challenging but extremely hard work! This was a turning point in my life when I realized, I controlled my future and that my dyslexia does not define me. I am in charge of what I achieve, do or become.  I enjoy working with people which is why I moved into coaching. I found that I have the ability to see the bigger picture, adapt to different situations and communicate well with people. When I asked friends what words they would use to describe me they said, happy, positive, determined, resilient, motivating, great listener, supportive, reliable, helpful, like to have a laugh, wild imagination, kind and caring to name just a few. #aspika #neurodiversity #dyslexia #dyslexicthinking #dyslexic #people #jobs #future #coaching #work #myfuture #yourfuture

‚ù§Ô∏è https://etsy.com/shop/AllMyLoveShops ü•∞ Promote #inclusion for all #neurodivergent individuals. ‚ôæ Every human brain works & acts uniquely. üåª Each mind has its own wire diagram. üåé Support #NeurodivergentAcceptance. #Neurodiversity is the concept that neurological differences, such as #autism, #ADHD, #dyslexia, and others, are not inherently negative or pathological, but rather are simply variations of the human experience. This idea is important because it recognizes that #neurodivergent individuals have unique strengths and perspectives that can benefit society as a whole. By embracing and celebrating neurodiversity, we can create a more #inclusive and #compassionate world that values #diversity and supports the full potential of all individuals. This means listening to and learning from neurodivergent individuals, promoting inclusion in all areas of life, and creating safe and supportive spaces that celebrate diversity. Neurodiversity #acceptance can also benefit individuals who do not identify as neurodivergent by promoting empathy, understanding, and acceptance of differences. When we acknowledge and value the diversity of human experiences, we can build a more tolerant and compassionate society that benefits everyone. It's important to remember that neurodiversity acceptance is not the same as ignoring or minimizing the challenges that neurodivergent individuals may face. Rather, it means recognizing that these challenges are often the result of societal barriers and prejudices, rather than inherent flaws in the individual. In short, neurodiversity acceptance is about recognizing and valuing the diversity of neurodivergent individuals, promoting inclusion and empathy, and building a society that celebrates differences and supports the full potential of all individuals. Let's work towards a world that embraces and celebrates neurodiversity, and recognizes the unique strengths and perspectives that neurodivergent individuals bring to the table.  #Neurodiversity #DifferentNotLess #InclusionMatters #NeurodivergentAcceptance #AutismAcceptance #AutismPride #AcceptanceNotAwareness #AutisticAndProud ‚ù§Ô∏èüíñü•∞

‚ùî‚ùîHave you heard this word? ‚ùî‚ùî The word ADVOCATE is both a noun and a verb. As a noun, an advocate is a person that publicly supports or recommends a particular cause or policy.  As a verb, to advocate means to publicly recommend or support.  In our world, it means to stand up for and represent a person that can‚Äôt speak up for themselves. An advocate is passionate about who they represent and what they stand for.  As a parent or guardian of a child with special needs, you are your child‚Äôs greatest advocate. No one is going to be more passionate about your child‚Äôs rights and education than you are.  Don‚Äôt be afraid to stand up for your child! Schwa matters! Schwa is all over the place. You schwa your words all the time. Schwa just means we are saying a short /u/ or a short /i/ sound in lieu of the written vowel. It keeps us from sounding like a robot. Schwa is easier to #read if you know the #word. Schwa is harder to #spell if you do not have that word, orthographically mapped in your brain. Let's talk about it! We do! These are words my student has been reading for a while BUT we still talk about them!  This helps them understand which letters make their regular sounds and which letters sound different in these specific words.  I am just loving thise strategy for TEACHING these irregular words vs having them memorize them.  Also, I read that we dont call these sight words because eventually, a majority of the words we read will hopefully fall into that category.  Instead, they are irregular words because they have letters that do not follow any phonics rules. This is why mapping these words and figuring out which letters do and do not follow the rules is extremely helpful to children when it comes to learning these words and committing it to their long term memory.  #specialeducation #specialeducationteacher #phonics #sightwords #highfrequency #heartwords #mapping #dyslexia #learntoread #dyslexiaawareness #readingskills #scienceofreading

Have you ever wondered how words are broken down in the English language?  Soccer Academy is made up of ELEVEN phonemes or individual sounds. /s/ - /o/ - /c/ - /er/ /a/ - /c/ - /a/ - /d/ - /e/ - /m/ - /y/ The letter s spells the /s/ sound. The vowel o can spell several sounds and is a great place to try vowel flexing. In this word, it spells the short o sound that sounds like /ah/. The letter c spells the /k/ sound. The letters er work together to spell the /er/ sound, and is most frequently found at the end of words. The letter a spells several different sounds, but in this word the first time it appears it spells the schwa sound, which sounds like /uh/. The letter c spells the /k/ sound. The letter a spells several different sounds, but in this word the second time it appears it spells the short a sound. The letter d spells the /d/ sound. The letter e spells several different sounds, but in this word, it spells the schwa sound, which sounds like /uh/. The letter m spells the /m/ sound. The letter y spells multiple sounds depending on where it is placed in a word. When it comes at the end of a multi-syllabic word, it makes the long e sound, which sounds like /ee/. People know that I am terrible at writing and reading due to my dyslexia. This often led to me being chosen last for group projects, as I couldn‚Äôt contribute much to the writing portion. Nowadays, people understand that I'm dyslexic, but I'm still smart; I just struggle with writing. We find ways to work around it, but it's hard sometimes when people think you're unintelligent just because you can't spell a word. It's not just my peers; my mentors and teachers also sometimes treat me as if I am incapable, despite my abilities in many areas. I couldn't advocate for myself in the past, and being called stupid in first grade for my inability to read and write stuck with me throughout my school years. Now, I don‚Äôt let teachers or classmates push me around anymore. As soon as they make any negative remark about my disability, I speak up. Having dyslexia, or any other learning disability, is normal, yet there's a taboo about it. People have had learning disabilities for a long time; we just never talked about them. Make it normal. #dyslexia #learningdisability #504 #504plan #iep :)

The good news about ##morphemesis their ##spellingand meaning is consistent. However, if one is not aware of morphemes then that meaning and consistency of ##spellingis lost. STITCH INCOMING! üö® üö® üö® Dyslexia is a learning disability that affects people's ability to read. However, many young people with dyslexia also have related difficulties that make school really hard for them üìñ‚úèÔ∏è Kids with dyslexia often have difficulties with writing, and especially with spelling. They take longer to complete reading and writing tasks, consequently running out of time on exams. This interferes with their ability to demonstrate the full range of their knowledge, thereby impacting their grades. These students often reverse their letters or write letters or numbers in the wrong order (e.g., 45 instead of 54). For dyslexics, reading is a slower, more labored process, and scenarios such as reading aloud in class can therefore be extremely anxiety-provoking. The awareness of their challenges can lead to avoidance of school or activities that require reading. Dyslexia can be treated but not cured. Although it is a lifelong struggle, with early identification, and appropriate interventions and support, dyslexic students can learn to read and write and lead successful lives. üîómychildassessment.com #childassessments #losangelesmom #explore #parenting #dyslexia #dyslexiamom #dyslexiaparenting #pediatricpsychologist #viral #parentingtok #comprehensiveassessments #trending #fyp #neurodivergenttok

Here‚Äôs the üçµ no one‚Äôs telling parents‚Ä¶. For many years there is this rumor that doctors can‚Äôt diagnose dyslexia until 8 or that teachers can‚Äôt identify dyslexia in an educational setting til 8. This rumor was basically created by bad and old information. The psychological tests used to diagnose dyslexia in medical settings and used by school psychologists used to only work on kids around 7 and older.  In the last ten years or so publishers of many of the tests used to diagnose dyslexia, adhd, dysgraphia and other learning disorders created versions that worked on kids 4-6.  It‚Äôs possible to diagnose dyslexia or other SLD Specific Learning Disorders as early as 4. Palmer Grasp Reflex. This reflex is connected to other primitive reflexes which means it controls more than one aspect of development however we will focus on fine motor skills. When the reflex is retained we find children who have a hard time with handwriting, tying shoes, opening zippers, working with buckles and buttons and anything with small intricate details. The exercise we're using here is "finger game". We started this exercise in the fall of 2021 where we did this exercise and others for 3 and a half months. When we first began, like all of the exercises we had to assist and make modifications for him until he built his way up. We took some time off and started back again 29 days ago. #palmargrasp #palmargraspreflex #sensoryissues #adhd #adhdkids #primitivereflexintegration #mellilomethod #primitivereflexes #auditoryprocessingdisorder #blackautismmoms #blackautism #autism #nonverbal #nonverbalchild #dyslexia

When a child is first diagnosed with autism, it can be overwhelming for parents. Here are 3 mistakes to avoid: 1. Trusting teachers alone: While educators have good intentions, most are not trained to successfully help autistic children.  2. Believing in a one-size-fits-all solution: Every autistic child's brain is unique, and what works for one child may not work for another.   3. Expecting a quick fix: Autism is a complex condition that cannot be cured, but with the right support and interventions, children can learn to thrive. Parents should avoid the trap of expecting a quick fix and instead focus on long-term strategies for their child's success. -> Check https://dyslexia.yale.edu/ for good resources! @imbriannamichelle #goodbeatparents #goodbeat #byparentsforparents #specialeducation #dyslexiaawareness #neurodiversity #dyslexia #dyslexicbrain #neurodiversity #DyslexicParenting #DyslexiaParenting.

I‚Äôm attempting to balance the complex full time maintenance that comes with this stupidly bendy glitchy body with my mental health and happiness. The age your child learns to read is not directly correlated to their success in life ü§Ø Now, we all know how important reading is. But it's not just the SKILL that's important. It's the LOVE of reading that will instill a foundation for learning. I felt so much pressure to make sure my daughter was hitting the mark before I learned this, and before I learned about her dyslexia. What did it say about me as a mom/homeschool mom if my daughter couldn't read "at her level"? As I began pressuring reading practice I started to notice her brain completely shut down after the first sentence. What was going on? She knows her letter sounds why can't she seem to muster them up even slowly? When she would consistently start her words with the last letter sound, that's when I started to wonder...and as I looked into it I confirmed she has dyslexia! If you want to learn more about this amazing gift üôåüèªit is not a learning disability!!üôåüèª hit the follow button as I share the things that have worked for us. Replying to @Olybrighteyes The Cat Kite spelling rule, or generalization, helps young learners know when to spell with a C or a K, since they make the same sound. We call this the hard sound of C. When C has EIY after it, it softens to the S sound - like center, cinnamon, cyan. The Catüêà‚Äç‚¨õü™ÅKite rule is beginning phonics and later they will learn the soft C. üòÉüòÉ NOTE: This is when those of us who are good readers and spellers, like to start coming up with all the exceptions to the Catüêà‚Äç‚¨õü™Å Kitr rule. And there are a lot of exceptions. But the exceptions just tell us that the word was not originated in English. ü§ìüßêThen it becomes a research project to figure out where we borrowed the word from like koala, kayak, karate, and even skunk. üëçüèºüëçüèºWords are talking to us if we will listen to them. #dyslexia #teachersoftiktok #iloveteaching #structuredliteracy #teacher #teach #smart #homeschool #spell #themoreyouknow #fyp„Ç∑ #spellingrules #elementary #kindergarten #catkite
